data.content:
Your code **doesn't use `Thread.Abort`** (or `ThreadAbortException`, `Thread.ResetAbort`, or `Thread.Interrupt`). It only uses `Thread.Start`, `Thread.Join`, and `Thread.Sleep` — all of which work identically in .NET 8. No migration is needed for Thread.Abort concerns.

That said, the modern .NET pattern for this kind of parallel work would be `Parallel.ForEach` or `Task.WhenAll`, which are simpler and more efficient:

```csharp
public async Task RunBatchAsync(List<WorkItem> items)
{
    await Parallel.ForEachAsync(items, async (item, ct) =>
    {
        await Task.Delay(100, ct);
        item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
    });
}
```

This gives you built-in cancellation support via `CancellationToken` if you need it later.
